[1] South Africa (Mpumalanga)
Date: 9 Sep 2005
From: Stephen Toovey <toovey@travelclinic.co.za>
Source: South African National Institute for Communicable Diseases [edited]

An outbreak of typhoid fever has been reported in Delmas, Mpumalanga.
Increases in diarrheal disease cases were noted on routine surveillance
from 15 Aug 2005. This prompted an investigation by the Provincial
Communicable Disease Directorate. Preliminary water testing revealed
evidence of fecal contamination of drinking water. Within 2-3 weeks of this
outbreak of diarrheal disease, cases began presenting with typical features
of typhoid fever. To date, at least 15 cases of typhoid fever have been
laboratory-confirmed on blood culture and 34 suspected cases have been
identified.
Health care workers should be alert to the possibility of typhoid fever in
both residents of Delmas and returning travelers from the area and amongst
contacts of cases. Many of the cases to date have been diagnosed in Gauteng
in patients who are attending school in Delmas or travelled to the area.
--
Dr Stephen Toovey
Johannesburg South Africa, Basel Switzerland
<toovey@travelclinic.co.za>
******
[2] South Africa (Mpumalanga)
Date: Fri, 9 Sep 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: SABCNews.com [edited]
<http://www.sabcnews.com/south_africa/health/0,2172,112084,00.html>

The number of confirmed typhoid cases in Delmas has risen to 116, with more
than 700 others suffering from diarrhea.
The typhoid-stricken town of Delmas in Mpumalanga will now be linked to the
water reticulation of the Rand Water network. This decision was finalized
at the 9 Sep 2005 meeting by stakeholders, who included the provincial
government and medical experts.
At first, people showed symptoms of diarrhea or fever. Early cases were at
an informal settlement on the outskirts of Delmas but it has since spread
across the town. Tap water is believed to be contaminated by human feces.
Tests show that an underground lake is infected with _E. coli_. The lake
feeds reservoirs in the area.
Residents have been asked to boil or purify water before using it. With
more patients being admitted to hospitals, extra doctors and nurses have
been deployed and the army has been asked to supply tents and set up field
hospitals
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
******
[3] Kyrgyzstan
Date: Fri, 9 Sep 2005
From: Alexander Peredkov <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Obshestvenniy reyting newspaper [trans. Mod.NR; edited]
<http://www.gsen.in.kg/ru/?news=3D13>

78 cases of typhoid fever have been reported in Kyrgyzstan during the last
8 months. This includes 20 cases in Osh city, 24 cases in the Osh region,
15 cases in the Jalajabad region, 14 in the Matken region, 3 in the Issik
Kul region, and one each in the Chuysk region and the capital city of
Bishkekhad. Traditionally the worst situation is observed at Nooken rayon
and Mauluu-Suu.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[ProMED-mail would like to thank Dr. Andrew Jamieson, Ms. Mary Marshall and
Dr. Jawad Asghar for 1st alerting us to the typhoid outbreak in South
Africa. - Mod.MPP]
[A rayon is a low-level territorial and administrative subdivision for
rural and municipal administration. A rural rayon is a county-sized
district in a territory or republic. A city rayon is similar to a borough
in some large cities in the USA - Mod.LL].
